        "content": "<p>Wow!  Lawvere had his <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/Hegelian+taco\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/Hegelian+taco\">Hegelian taco</a>, and we all know that a <a href=\"https://blog.plover.com/prog/burritos.html\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"https://blog.plover.com/prog/burritos.html\">monad is like a burrito</a>, but now there are <a href=\"http://www.tac.mta.ca/tac/volumes/35/12/35-12.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"http://www.tac.mta.ca/tac/volumes/35/12/35-12.pdf\">enchilada categories</a>:</p>",
        "id": 191668916,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1585082245
    },
    {
        "content": "<div class=\"codehilite\"><pre><span></span>Exact sequences in the enchilada category\n\nM. Eryüzlü, S. Kaliszewski, and John Quigg\n\nWe define exact sequences in the enchilada category of C*-algebras and\ncorrespondences, and prove that the reduced-crossed-product functor is not\nexact for the enchilada categories. Our motivation was to determine\nwhether we can have a better understanding of the Baum-Connes conjecture\nby using enchilada categories. Along the way we prove numerous results\nshowing that the enchilada category is rather strange.\n\nTheory and Applications of Categories, Vol. 35, 2020, No. 12, pp 350-370.\n\nhttp://www.tac.mta.ca/tac/volumes/35/12/35-12.pdf\n</pre></div>",
        "id": 191669057,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1585082297
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I always thought that burritos more comonadic than monadic. Perhaps the tortilla endofunctor has some deeper underlying structure</p>",
        "id": 191669712,
        "sender_full_name": "Reed Mullanix",
        "timestamp": 1585082618
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Many other people have studied this under a less hip, but more informative name. Also, they actually look at the bicategory, not the homotopy category, which is better. Also, I believe the 1-arrows they use (apart from committing the error of truncating) are not general enough. I can come up with easy maps between spaces such that the induced maps between C*-algebras aren't in their category.</p>",
        "id": 191705158,
        "sender_full_name": "David Michael Roberts",
        "timestamp": 1585118360
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Other than that, I do want to understand what they do, because I have a long-incubating project on a related (bi)category</p>",
        "id": 191705165,
        "sender_full_name": "David Michael Roberts",
        "timestamp": 1585118393
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276422\">David Michael Roberts</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229136-category-theory/topic/enchilada.20categories/near/191705158\" title=\"#narrow/stream/229136-category-theory/topic/enchilada.20categories/near/191705158\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Many other people have studied this under a less hip, but more informative name. Also, they actually look at the bicategory, not the homotopy category, which is better. Also, I believe the 1-arrows they use (apart from committing the error of truncating) are not general enough. I can come up with easy maps between spaces such that the induced maps between C*-algebras aren't in their category.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>A naive question: You said that looking at the bicategory is better. Would it make sense to look at the double category instead (with *-homomorphisms as vertical arrows and correspondences as horizontal arrows)?</p>",
        "id": 191727246,
        "sender_full_name": "Nicolas Blanco",
        "timestamp": 1585133242
    },
    {
        "content": "<blockquote>\n<p>Many other people have studied this under a less hip, but more informative name. Also, they actually look at the bicategory, not the homotopy category, which is better.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Can you sketch what bicategory you're talking about?   (I have <em>no</em> idea what this enchilada category is; I just found the name amusing.)</p>",
        "id": 191805543,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1585167458
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"275920\">@John Baez</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229136-category-theory/topic/enchilada.20categories/near/191805543\" title=\"#narrow/stream/229136-category-theory/topic/enchilada.20categories/near/191805543\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Many other people have studied this under a less hip, but more informative name. Also, they actually look at the bicategory, not the homotopy category, which is better.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Can you sketch what bicategory you're talking about?   (I have <em>no</em> idea what this enchilada category is; I just found the name amusing.)</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I believe it would have C *-algebras as objects,  C *-correspondences as morphisms and <del>Morita-Rieffel equivalences</del> intertwiners as 2-morphisms. The more informative name would then be a correspondence bicategory. You might be interested in this because C *-correspondences are spans. Ralf Meyer and his school have written a lot about this.</p>",
        "id": 191831476,
        "sender_full_name": "(=_=)",
        "timestamp": 1585186063
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Paging <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"277271\">@Min Ro</span>: you might find this interesting.</p>",
