    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276422\">David Michael Roberts</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229136-category-theory/topic/enchilada.20categories/near/191855898\" title=\"#narrow/stream/229136-category-theory/topic/enchilada.20categories/near/191855898\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276120\">Nicolas Blanco</span> that's even better: it would then be some kind of pseudo-double category. I have my own views on using bimodules rather than a certain class of cospans, but the result should be biequivalent</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Yes, I had in mind this rough analogy with the (pseudo-?)double category of rings, ring homomorphisms and bimodules. Or more generally with the pseudo-double category of enriched categories, enriched functors and enriched profunctors.<br>\nI am not sure if this analogy can be made more precise though.</p>",
